In the United States, Six Sigma is decentralized. However, only three institutional frameworks truly "stick" and carry legal/regulatory weight:ASQ (American Society for Quality): The gold standard for US manufacturing, aerospace, and defense. Does not last forever. It requires mandatory re-validation or audits every 3 years. Bypassing an audit lapses the credential.IASSC (International Association for Six Sigma Certification): Standard for corporate commercial tech and global enterprise. Operated via PeopleCert, requiring re-certification exam cycles every 3 years.CSSC (The Council for Six Sigma Certification): Popular for providing "Lifetime" certifications that do not expire.🪖 "Special Conduct & Forces" (Federal & Military variant)The US Armed Forces (Army, Navy, Air Force) utilize LSS (Lean Six Sigma) CPI (Continuous Process Improvement) task forces. Military Black Belts are strictly governed by Federal Ethics Rules (5 CFR Part 2635) and the Uniform Code of Military Justice (UCMJ). Misrepresenting project metrics, falsifying cost savings (ROI inflation on government spending), or abandoning control protocols can result in formal administrative reprimands under Article 92 (Dereliction of Duty) or Article 107 (False Official Statements).